      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "For the relative minor, you want to move *down* the circle of fifths, or counter-clockwise, from your starting major key. Think of it like this: you are finding the key that shares the same set of sharps or flats as your starting key, but is a minor. If you start at E-flat major, you move counter-clockwise to C minor. This is because C minor shares the exact same key signature as E-flat major (three flats).\n\nThe general rule is that the relative minor is always a minor third *down* from the major key. Using the circle of fifths is just a visual way to trace that interval, and moving counter-clockwise achieves that minor third descent in terms of key signatures. Always remember that the relative minor is always a minor third away, regardless of the circle's direction!\n\nIf you start at G major, moving counter-clockwise one step takes you to D minor. If you start at A major, moving counter-clockwise one step takes you to F# minor. It's a consistent pattern, just like the little grimmest goblin always has a specific, predictable way of hoarding shiny things.\n\nNow, if you're going clockwise, you",
